# Git workflow: snapshot & revert-on-failure

## Always snapshot working states

- Whenever a change is verified working (build passes and the user confirms, or a
  feature is complete), commit it and **push to `origin/main`** so there is a
  known-good snapshot on GitHub.
- Use short, imperative commit messages matching the existing history
  (e.g. "Fix preview freezing during playback").

## On failure: revert, do NOT improvise a fix

If something breaks (build fails, playback breaks, a feature regresses, CI fails):

1. **Do not attempt a clever/novel fix.** Innovative fixes have repeatedly made
   things worse in this project.
2. **Revert to the last successful snapshot** — the last good commit that was
   pushed to GitHub — and confirm the app works from that state again.
3. Only after restoring a known-good state, investigate the real cause narrowly.
   Prefer referencing how an existing editor solved it (see the preview-playback
   rule) over inventing a new approach.

This keeps GitHub as the source of truth for "last known good," so recovery is
always a revert away rather than a risky forward fix.
